 of the HPV vaccine. The book contextualizes the background for how gendered risk was mediated by two groups of women: mothers negotiating the vaccine for their daughters in school-based immunization programs and university students who experienced frequent HPV infections. The book explores these women’s efforts to be good mothers and strong young women entering adulthood who felt vulnerable in sexual health negotiation. As a result, Making Gender reveals how vaccine decision-making took an ontological form, as an inherently social and cultural process embedded in women’s experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDecision making. 0aMedical policyzCanada. 0aMothers and daughterszCanada. 0aPapillomavirus vaccineszCanada. 0aPapillomavirus vaccines. 0aPharmaceutical industryzCanada. 0aPharmaceutical industry. 0aVaccinationxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aVaccinationzCanadaxDecision making. 0aWomen college studentsxHealth risk assessmentzCanada. 0aWomenxHealth risk assessmentzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aHPV vaccine.  aHPV.  agender and the HPV vaccine.  agender and vaccine.  ahuman sexuality.  apublic health policy.  avaccine decision making.  avaccine policy development.  avaccine policy.  avaccines and health equity.40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753989440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487539894423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487539894/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles